There was a problem loading comments right now. Please try again later.4.0 out of 5 starsNot just another book on Hitler and World War IIBywilliam mathewson August 15, 2013Format: Kindle Edition|Verified PurchaseEvans puts a unique twist on the German experience in WWII; the military history, if one wants it is there in the foundation of the scholarship of the Freiburg military experts, but the war was in many ways a foregone conclusion as Evans shows; the Third Reich's priority was its drive for a New Order of social and racial cleansing in which it must be said the military effort often played a second fiddle in the orchestration of a 'final solution' to first the Polish question, then the Jewish question, the Serb question, the gypsies and more broadly social alien questions fused together in a Nazi modernist ideology of progressive and positivist social engineering to eliminate what the Nazis and their allies in government saw as social smut. Evans orchestrates a vast amount of scholarship from others into very startling and readable form. One can read this third volume of his trilogy on the Third Reich and come away with a sense of intellectual satisfaction, that he has explained what happened and what mattered. The publishers should, however, be impaled for recurrent screw ups with nearly all (but not all!) foreign accent marks, which somehow wind up blemishing the text.0Comment|
